Inspired by https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/34320#discussion_r2751764873.

### Problem
`std::move` for [trivially copyable](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/is_trivially_copyable.html) types is redundant in a few remaining cases in the codebase. It looks like a possible compiler hint but in fact it's just misleading.
For trivially copyable types there is no user-defined resource transfer, moving is semantically the same as copying the bytes. There's no resource to steal, so `std::move()` can't make it cheaper, it's just confusing (GCC/Clang typically emit identical code in `-O2`, see https://godbolt.org/z/hdrn17v9b).

Enabling the clang-tidy plugin reveals a few problems, see: https://github.com/l0rinc/bitcoin/actions/runs/21691481371/job/62552391428?pr=114

### Fix
Remove a few of the remaining `std::move` instances in the code and enable `performance-move-const-arg` warnings to enforce it in follow-ups.

